ANOVA report

07 giugno 2018

0. Report structure

This a report automatically generated by the DIY_ANOVA app (https://pecostats.shinyapps.io/DIY_ANOVA/). It consists of the following sections:

  1. Input data
  2. Normality
  3. Homoscedasticity
  4. ANOVA results
  5. Post-hoc test

1. Input data

The input dataset has 48 records and 4 variables: SUBJECT, GENDER, DOSE, SCORE. For the following analysis, GENDER, DOSE will be modelled as categorical predictive variables (factors), and SCORE as a continuous response variable.

2. Normality

A One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test was performed on the response variable was significant (D statistic = 0.1269, p-value = 0.4221). The distribution of the response variable, therefore, is significantly significantly different from a normal distribution with the same mean and variance.

The followings charts are: on the left a QQ plot produced to compare the distribution quantiles of the response variable with the theoretical quantiles of a normal distribution; on the right a bar chart that provides a visual representation of the distribution of the response variable itself.

3. Homoscedasticity

Homogeneity of variances (i.e. homoscedasticity) was tested via Bartlett’s K-squared test on SCORE by GENDER, DOSE. This test was significant (Bartlett’s K-squared statistic = 10.59, p-value = 0.01418). The variance of the response variable among groups, therefore, cannot be assumed to be homogeneous.

4. ANOVA results

4.1. ANOVA model and table

Factors were defined as follows: GENDER as fixed, DOSE as fixed, and the linear model underlying this ANOVA is

SCORE ~ GENDER * DOSE
